A radial engine is a type of internal combustion engine typically used in aircraft. Its called radial because the cylinders are arranged in a circular pattern 
around the crankshaft, resembling the spokes of a wheel or the rays of a sun.
Radial engines were popular in aviation during the early to mid-20th century, especially in World War I and World War II aircraft. They were known for their reliability,
relatively simple design, and high power-to-weight ratio. 
The airflow over the cylinders provided effective cooling, which was advantageous in aviation applications:







